[{"sha":"0ca284125ae6319683cacd0044699a996f4c4e1c","author":{"name":"Andrew Or","email":"a5c478d606458f6c868a5126471748acd4730a6f@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix heterogeneous + virtual nodes convergence (round 2)

This reverts b4ec231 and 1b7204c. The previous approach of
summing all losses and then dividing by the global batch size
proved to be problematic with virtual nodes. This is because
when we sum across the virtual nodes on a device, we end up
summing the regularization losses as well, but these losses
were not scaled by the global batch size. However, we can't
simply average across the virtual nodes either, because that
would by double dividing.

Instead, we try a new approach. We perform a weighted average
for gradient synchronization instead. This allows us to keep
averaging across the virtual nodes on the same device. The
scaling factor is applied when the losses are computed as in
the previous code.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/andrewor14/tensorflow/commits/0ca284125ae6319683cacd0044699a996f4c4e1c"}]

The test has race condition, which is addressed by the patch.

The race is next:

    Master thread is calling execute (effectively blocked, waiting for
callback to be called)
    "Async" thread picks up the callback
    Call the callback
    Then sets the variables in test
    After call back is called, master thread is unblocked and may check
the variables (set in point 4 by the "async" thread) earlier then they
actually changed

Changes:

    callback should be called as the last step (after flag variables are

* Synchronously render children of a Suspense boundary

[{"sha":"e22a98458b78c224756791023157938391416cc9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/e22a98458b78c224756791023157938391416cc9"}]

Change-Id: Ib5ef2e6067a601726d7c2ce787b7357049850f37","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yaochengji/tensorflow/commits/0979d2adf2d92566960eba4c3ef27e6a7cf5b8bc"},{"sha":"550a60b9823f7c0f0f3bbc61931e5e64199e9985","author":{"name":"Jaesung Chung","email":"935e11c5b050a3a02c4f0e08de55daf431709deb@google.com"},"message":"Introduce a new experimental and private converter flag to put user's TFLite
custom op libraries into calibrator.

When TFLite custom ops were enabled in a model, the calibrator will always be
broken at finding TFLite custom op handlers since the calibration_wrapper just
uses the TFLite builtin op resolver always.

By using the new experimental and private flag,
converter.target_spec._experimental_custom_op_registerers,
users will enable post training quantization with calibrations for the models
that contain user provided TFLite custom op libraries.

Usage:

converter = tf.lite.TFLiteConverter.from_keras_model(model)
converter.optimizations = [lite.Optimize.DEFAULT]
converter.representative_dataset = calibration_gen
converter.allow_custom_ops = True
converter.target_spec._experimental_custom_op_registerers = [
  "AddHashTableOps", "AddStringOps"
]

retain a large amount of memory. React-managed DOM nodes also point
back to a fiber tree.

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"}]

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"}]

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"}]

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Muhammadariesta/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"},{"sha":"9d48779b362ef773da50fef95af6998b560c75c0","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fixed broken feature flag import for DT inline package (#21237)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Muhammadariesta/react/commits/9d48779b362ef773da50fef95af6998b560c75c0"}]

end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to

The host tree is a cyclical structure. Leaking a single DOM node can
retain a large amount of memory. React-managed DOM nodes also point
back to a fiber tree.

Perf testing suggests that disconnecting these fields has a big memory
impact. That suggests leaks in non-React code but since it's hard to
completely eliminate those, it may still be worth the extra work to
clear these fields.

for the memory savings, or if there are other fields that are retaining
large amounts of memory.

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yohanceli/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"}]

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chanhong/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"}]

[{"sha":"bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"}]
